'''Abigail Rogers''' (1818–1869) was an American advocate for [[women's rights]] and [[women's education]]. She founded the Michigan Women's College, and was posthumously inducted into the [[Michigan Women's Hall of Fame]] in 2007.
== Biography == Rogers spent her whole life advocating for the admittance of women into Michigan universities. In September 1855, she founded the Michigan Women's College in [[Lansing, Michigan]] with Delia Rogers and pioneer James Turner<ref>{{cite book |last1=Dunbar|first1= Willis F.|last2=May |first2=George S.|date= 5 September 1995 |title=Michigan: A History of the Wolverine State |url=https://books.google.co.nz/books?id=HqGWEAnByeMC |location=Grand Rapids, MI |publisher= Wm. B. Eerdmans |page=296|isbn= 9780802870551 |author-link= }}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://lansingcitypulse.com/article-14544-Love-at-last-for-the-Abigail.html |title=Love at last for the Abigail? |last=Cosentino |first=Lawrence |date=22 March 2017 |website= City Pulse |publisher= |access-date=8 December 2017 |quote=}}</ref>, with the stated goal "to keep before the public mind as constantly as they could, the duty of the State to provide for the education of its daughters as it had already provided for the education of its sons." The college held daily sessions in the [[Michigan State Capitol]] until acquiring a location of their own in 1857. Ten years later over 1000 students had been educated. In 1869, Rogers died. Later that same year, in part as a result of her work [[Michigan State University]] (in 1869) admitted women, and the next year, the [[University of Michigan]] (in 1870) admitted women. The Michigan Women's College would eventually become the Michigan School for the Blind.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.lansingmi.gov/955/Michigan-Female-College|title=Michigan Female College {{!}} Lansing, MI|website=www.lansingmi.gov|language=en|access-date=2017-11-28}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.michiganwomenshalloffame.org/Images/Rogers,%20Abigail.pdf|title=Abigail Rogers|last=|first=|date=|website=Michigan Women's Hall of Fame|archive-url=|archive-date=|dead-url=|access-date=}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.cadl.org/news/2017/03/15/michigan-women-in-history/ |title=Michigan Women in History |last= |first= |date=15 March 2017 |website=Capital Area District Libraries |publisher= |access-date=8 December 2017 |quote=}}</ref>
