'''Educology''' is the study of [[education]], or more precisely, '''educological research (or inquiry)''' is the study of education, and '''educology is the product of the study''', provided that the study is careful, disciplined, successful research (or inquiry) which treats education as the dependent variable and which examines the effects of other variables upon education.<ref>{{cite book |last1=Steiner |first1=Elizabeth |title=Educology of the Free |year=1981 |publisher=Philosophical Library |location=New York |isbn=0-8022-2373-7}}</ref>

==Overview==

The term '''''educology''''' denotes the fund of knowledge about education.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Fisher|first=James E|title=Contributing Paper 1.1 in History and Philosophy of Educology, Part I (A paper used as the basis for a series of seven lectures to faculty and doctoral students in educology at Vytautas Magnus University (VMU) in December, 2001)|journal=Pedagogika|publisher=Kaunus, Lithuania: Vytauto Didziojo universiteto leidykla|year=2001|url=http://www.era-usa.net/contributingpapersset1.html|issn= 1392-0340}}</ref> The fund consists of the entire set of recorded true statements about education. Educology includes
# '''facts''' (verified accurate descriptions) about the field of phenomena denoted by the term ''education'',
# '''theories''' (highly plausible and well supported explanations) about how, why and when things happen as they do in education,
# '''evaluations and recommendations''' (judgments about the worth of states of affairs in education and recommendations for action to take or avoid in relation to education) and
# '''justifications''' (sound reasons based on norms and criteria) for evaluations and prescriptions made for states of affairs in education.
Some basic warranted assertions about education which have been produced by educological research and inquiry include:
# '''Education is a social system'''. It consists of the elements of teacher, student, content and setting (physical, social and cultural). In education, someone, playing the role of teacher, provides guidance and opportunities to study, and someone else, playing the role of student, intentionally studies under guidance some content (some fund of knowledge and/or some exemplification of knowing) within some physical, social and cultural setting with a view in mind that the student extends his or her range of knowing and understanding. 
# '''Education can be official or unofficial'''. Official education occurs in schools, colleges, universities and the like. Unofficial education occurs in families, in peer groups, with work colleagues, etc.
# '''Education can be effective or ineffective'''. Students can undertake to learn something and not achieve the intended learning outcomes, in which case the education has been ineffective. Or students can undertake to learn something and achieve the intended learning outcomes, in which case, the education has been effective. 
# '''Education can be good or bad'''. Bad education may have either unworthwhile, inethical, immoral, etc. intended learning outcomes or it may use undesirable, inethical, immoral, etc. means to achieve intended learning outcomes, or both conditions may exist. Good education has both worthwhile intended learning outcomes, and it employs desirable (ethical, worthy, moral, etc.) means of achieving the intended learning outcomes.
# '''Education either constructs, maintains or reconstructs social and cultural norms'''. Both official and unofficial education function, under various circumstances (political, economic, religious, historical, etc.), either to construct, maintain or reconstruct (improve, reform) the prevalent norms of the social and cultural setting in which the educational process is operating.
# '''Learning from education is intentional and guided'''. Whether official or unofficial, learning from education is intentional guided learning. It is achieved through intentional guidance and intentional study. Intentional guided learning contrasts with coerced learning, accidental learning and discovery learning. Coerced learning is achieved through the processes of socialization, enculturation, indoctrination and psychological conditioning. Accidental learning is achieved through misadventures, mishaps, catastrophes and chance experiences. Discovery learning is achieved through systematic inquiry, careful disciplined research and trial & error.

Educology consists of knowledge about all aspects of education, official and unofficial, effective and ineffective, good and bad. It includes knowledge (recorded true statements) about
# '''patterns and meanings of discourse''' among teachers, students and third parties in the educational process,
# '''past states of affairs''' in education, including what happened, why it happened, what followed,
# '''extant states of affairs''' in education, including what happens, why it happens, what will happen given some set of conditions,
# '''effective practices and relations''' instrumental for achieving desired states of affairs in education and avoiding and/or eliminating undesired states of affairs in education,
# '''good and bad states of affairs''' for and in education and
# '''laws, rules and regulations''' which govern education.
For the purposes of research and guided study, educology is commonly organized into subsets or subfunds of educology. The organization is done in relation to features or aspects in the field of phenomena of education that are being researched and/or studied under guidance. Common subfunds of educology include
# '''the educology of mind (or psyche)''', which includes the part of psychology of education that treats education as the dependent variable,
# '''the educology of society''', which includes the part of sociology of education that treats education as the dependent variable,
# '''the educology of economic systems''', which includes the part of economics of education that treats education as the dependent variable,
# '''the educology of culture''', which includes the part of anthropology of education that treats education as the dependent variable,
# '''the educology of nations''', which is the same subfund of educology denoted by the term ''comparative and international education'',
# '''the educology of past states of affairs in education''', which is the same subfund of educology denoted by the term ''history of education'',
# '''the educology of good states of affairs in education''', which is the same subfund of educology denoted by the term ''philosophy of education'',
# '''the educology of effective teaching and effective guided studying''', which is the subfund of educology that includes more than, but is partly denoted by the term ''studies of teaching strategies and methodologies'' and partly denoted by the term ''productive pedagogies'',
# '''the educology of administration''', which is the same subfund of educology denoted by the term ''educational administration studies'',
# '''the educology of counseling and guidance''', which is the same subfund of educology denoted by the term ''studies of school counseling and guidance'',
# '''the educology of curriculum''', which is the same subfund of educology denoted by the term ''curriculum studies'',
# '''the educology of early childhood education''', which is the same subfund of educology denoted by the term ''early childhood education studies'',
# '''the educology of elementary education''', which is the same subfund of educology denoted by the term ''elementary education studies'',
# '''the educology of secondary education''', which is the same subfund of educology denoted by the term ''secondary education studies'',
# '''the educology of higher education''', which is the same subfund of educology denoted by the term ''higher education studies'',
# '''the educology of adult education''', which is the same subfund of educology denoted by the term ''adult education studies'',
# '''the educology of assessment and evaluation''', which is the subfund of educology that includes more than, but is partly denoted by the term ''studies of tests and measurements'',
# '''the educology of mathematics education''' which is the same subfund of educology denoted by the term ''mathematics education studies'',
# '''the educology of music education''' which is the same subfund of educology denoted by the term ''music education studies'',
# '''the educology of science education''' which is the same subfund of educology denoted by the term ''science education studies'',
# '''the educology of [any aspect of education]''', i.e. recorded true statements about any feature or characteristic of the set of phenomena denoted by the term ''education'', including any aspect of teachers, students, content and setting and any relation (e.g. dependent, independent, coincidental, causal, constructive, destructive, reconstructive, sustaining, etc.) among those four elements of education.
Development of educology commenced in the 1950s. Since that time, educology has been extended through publication of research findings in journals and books and through the establishment of departments of educology and the provision of educology courses in universities.<ref name=brezinkaetal>See:
