==History and etymology==

===Use from the 1950s through the 1970s===
The term '''''educology''''' has been in use in the English language since the seminal work in educology by Professor Lowry W. Harding<ref>Lowry Harding published four works in educology. They have a light hearted tone, but there is a serious underlying message about the necessity to clarify the distinction between the educational process and knowledge about that process:
* {{cite book |editor-first=Lowry W| editor-last=Harding|title=Anthology in Educology|year=1951 |publisher=Wm C Brown, Co |location=Dubuque, Iowa}}
* {{cite book |editor-first=Lowry W| editor-last=Harding|title=Essays in Educology|year=1956 |publisher=Wm C Brown, Co |location=Dubuque, Iowa}}
* {{cite book |editor-first=Lowry W| editor-last=Harding|title=More Essays in Educology|year=1964 |publisher=Association for the Study of Educology |location=Columbus, Ohio}}
* {{cite book |editor-first=Lowry W| editor-last=Harding|title=Educology: The Fourth Collection|year=1965 |publisher=Association for the Study of Educology |location=Columbus, Ohio}}</ref> at [[Ohio State University]] in the 1950s and Professor Elizabeth Steiner [Maccia]<ref>Elizabeth Steiner Maccia published under the names of Elizabeth Steiner and Elizabeth Steiner Maccia:
* {{Cite journal|last=Maccia|first=Elizabeth Steiner|title=Logic of Education and of Educatology: Dimensions of Philosophy of Education|journal=Proceedings of the Twentieth Annual Conference of the Philosophy of Education Society|publisher=Lawrence, Kansas: Philosophy of Education Society| year=1964|issn=8756-6575}}
* {{Cite journal|last=Maccia|first=Elizabeth Steiner|title=Towards Educational Theorizing without Mistake|journal=Studies in Philosophy and Education|volume=7|issue=2|pages=154–157|date=Sep 1970|issn=0039-3746|doi=10.1007/bf00372558}}
