* {{Cite journal|last=Brady|first=Laurie|title=Outcome Based Education: Imposing a Model for Curriculum Development|journal=International Journal of Educology|volume=9|issue=2|pages=180–192|publisher=Educology Research Associates|year=1995|url=http://catalogue.nla.gov.au/Record/1438074?lookfor=international%20journal%20of%20educology&offset=2&max=726406|issn=0818-0563}}</ref> Berdine F. Nel,<ref>{{cite book |last1=Nel |first1=Berdine F |title=From Fundamental Pedagogics to Educology: A Solution or a Substitution |year=1980 |publisher=South African Association for Advancement of Education |location=Durban, Natal |isbn=0-909072-33-7}}</ref> Maryann J. Ehle<ref>{{cite book |last=Ehle|first=Maryann |editor-first=James E| editor-last=Christensen |title=Educology 86: Proceedings of a Conference on Educational Research, Inquiry and Development with an Educological Perspective, Canberra, July 10-12, 1986|publisher=Sydney: Educology Research Associates |year=1986 |pages=34–50|chapter=Chapter 3: The Educology of Self Perception |isbn=0-949784-05-2}}</ref> and others.<ref>For others who have contributed to the development of educology, see {{Citation|title=International Journal of Educology|publisher=Educology Research Associates|date=1987–2015 |url=http://catalogue.nla.gov.au/Record/1438074?lookfor=international%20journal%20of%20educology&offset=2&max=726406|issn=0818-0563}}, in which more than 100 articles in educology have been published to date.</ref>

===Developments since the 1980s===
In Europe, development of educology in the 1980s and 1990s came from the research of Anton Monshouwer,<ref>See

* {{cite book |last=Monshouwer|first=Anton |editor-first=James E| editor-last=Christensen |title=Perspectives on Education as Educology |publisher=Washington, DC: University Press of America|year=1981 |pages=51–86|chapter=Chapter 3: The Formal Structure of an Emerging Science of Education, Part I: Some Opinions about the Scientific Status of a Science of Education |isbn=0-8191-1394-8}}
* {{cite book |last=Monshouwer|first=Anton |editor-first=James E| editor-last=Christensen |title=Perspectives on Education as Educology |publisher=Washington, DC: University Press of America|year=1981 |pages=159–196|chapter=Chapter 7: The Formal Structure of an Emerging Science of Education, Part II: The Concept of Science |isbn=0-8191-1394-8}}</ref> Theo Oudkerk Pool,<ref>{{cite book |last=Pool|first=Theo Oudkerk |editor-first=James E| editor-last=Christensen |title=Educology 86: Proceedings of a Conference on Educational Research, Inquiry and Development with an Educological Perspective, Canberra, July 10-12, 1986|publisher=Sydney: Educology Research Associates |year=1986 |pages=182–220|chapter=Chapter 12: Teacher Education in an Educological Perspective |isbn=0-949784-05-2}}</ref> [[Wolfgang Brezinka]],<ref>Of Wolfgang Brezinka's many publications, two of the most important ones in English are:

* {{cite book |last=Brezinka|first=Wolfgang |editor-first=James E| editor-last=Christensen |title=Perspectives on Education as Educology |publisher=Washington, DC: University Press of America|year=1981 |pages=7–26|chapter=Chapter 1: Meta-Theory of Education: European Contributions from an Empirical-Analytic Point of View |isbn=0-8191-1394-8}}
* {{cite book |last1=Brezinka |first1=Wolfgang (Translated from the German by James Stuart Brice and Raoul Eshelman) |title=Philosophy of Educational Knowledge: An Introduction to the Foundations of Science of Education, Philosophy of Education and Practical Pedagogics|year=1992 |publisher=Kluwer Academic Publishers |location=Dordrecht |isbn=0-7923-1522-7}}</ref> Carlos E. Olivera,<ref>{{Cite journal | last1=Olivera | first1=Carlos E. | title=Comparative Education: Towards a Basic Theory  | journal=Prospects | volume=18 | issue=2 | pages=167–185 | publisher=UNESCO | date=1988 | url=https://link.springer.com/journal/11125 | issn=0033-1538 | doi=10.1007/bf02195515}}</ref> Nikola Pastuovic<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Pastuovic|first=Nikola|title=The Science(s) of Adult Education|journal=International Journal of Lifelong Education|volume=14|issue=4|pages=273–291|publisher=Routledge Taylor & Francis Group|year=1995|url=http://www.informaworld.com/smpp/content~content=a746845434&db=all|issn=0260-1370|doi=10.1080/0260137950140402}}</ref> and in the early 2000s by Birgitta Qvarsell,<ref>{{cite book |last=Qvarsell|first=Birgitta |editor-first=Birgitta| editor-last=Qvarsell |editor2-first=Christoph|editor2-last=Wulf |title=Culture and Education. European Studies in Education. Volume 16 |publisher=Munster, Germany: Waxman|year=2003|pages=13–24 |chapter=Cultures as a Construction for Educational Research |isbn=3-8309-1227-7}}</ref> Kestutis Pukelis and Izabela Savickiene<ref>{{Cite journal|last1=Pukelis|first1=Kestutis|last2=Savickiene|first2=Izabela|title=The Challenge of Establishing a Common Set of Terms for Discourse, Inquiry, and Research in Educational Science: An Analytically Oriented Philosophy of Educology|journal=International Journal of Educology|volume=Lithuanian Special Issue|pages=14–27|publisher=Educology Research Associates|year=2005|url=http://www.eric.ed.gov/PDFS/ED494894.pdf|issn=0818-0563}}</ref> and Sharon Link.<ref>{{cite book |last1=Link |first1=Sharon | title= Educology  |year=2008  |url=http://www.dswleads.com/Ebsco/Educology.pdf |publisher= EBSCO Research Starters, EBSCO Publishing Inc}}</ref> Recent contributions to the development of educology have come from the American educologists Theodore W. Frick of Indiana University, Bloomington,<ref>See

